Domestic Beers and Breweries

Mai Loan Tran/Zackary Gill

October 16, 2018

Introduction

We have been asked to help Budweiser identify which states should host events for breweries. The two provided datasets contain lists of 2410 US craft beers across 558 US breweries consisting of the style of beer, ABV (Alcohol by Volume), IBU (International Bitterness Units), and the brewerys city and state. An analysis was done on this data in order to provide recommendations to the CEO and CFO of Budweiser. Before stating the recommendations, we will give an overview of the data analysis that is used to generate them.

Question 7

Chart 9 reflects an apparent positive relationship between IBU and ABV values.
The black dotted line is the mean ABV at that value of IBU. The yellow shading is the standard deviation. While there is positive correlation between the ABV and IBU with a maximum ABV value peaking out around 10%, there are two outliers that warrant further examination for inclusion or exclusion depending on additional questions of interest. When answering those specific additional questions we would want to use something like Pearsons r to gain an more precise answer.

Chart 9: Alcohol By Volume vs International Bitterness Units of beer

Conclusion

Based on the data above we have three recommendations. First we propose the events to be hosted in the states with the most number of breweries (Colorado [47], California [39], Michigan [32], Oregon [29], Texas [28]). As shown in Chart 1, this presents opportunities to expand services in those existing markets. The second recommendation is to host the events in the states that have the least amount of breweries (South Dakota [1], North Dakota [1], West Virginia [1]) which gives an opportunity to grow those markets. The final approach to the event selection is to host the events in the states that have the highest median IBU (Maine [61], West Virginia [57.5], Florida [55], Georgia [55], and Delaware [52]; see Chart 6.). There, we will bring beer that has similar style/ABV to the local beers but with a lower IBU (tastes less bitter) in order to gain market share.
